The per capita N footprints between international and domestic trades in Thailand were 19.07 and 19.33 kg N capita−1 yr−1 in 2017. The food portion of the N footprint was 11.08−11.35 kg Ncapita−1 yr−1, with the food production contribution of 95−97% and food consumption contribution of 3−5%. Next, 62.8% and 63.1% of the food N footprint with and without trades were from animal products (Fig. 4
                        ), where the main contributors were poultry (32.65−33.13%) and beef (11.01-11.43%). For crop products, rice (cereal product) was found to have the highest N footprint at 3.87−4.00 kg Ncapita−1 yr−1 (35.26−34.97%), followed by pineapple at N footprint at 0.14 kg N capita−1 yr−1 (1.25−1.28%) and baby corn which contribute the lowest impact at 0.07 kg Ncapita−1 yr−1 (0.61−0.63%). In the energy sector, the total energy N footprint was 7.98 kg N capita−1 yr−1 (Fig. 7). The largest sector contributing to the energy N footprint was transportation (6.83 kg N capita−1 yr−1). Household energy consumption contributes 0.79 kg Ncapita−1 yr−1 and goods & services contribute 0.37 kg N capita−1 yr−1. The NG consumption was the main cause of the total energy N footprint which accounted for 80.62% of the total N losses for the energy sector (Fig. 5−7

                        ). Thailand Greenhouse Gas Management Organization (2009) reported that the majority of fossil energy resources of Thai electricity grid included NG (75.70%), coal (11.8%), lignite (12.86%) and fossil oil (0.48%). The reactive N release mainly came from air emission (Fig. 7
                        (a) and Fig. 7(b)) because of anthropogenic nitrogen oxide emission from the combustions of petroleum, particularly coal and power generation which are predominantly NOx compounds (Olable and Slep, 2003). Therefore, reducing activities that require the use of fossil and increasing renewable energy resources to substitute fossil fuels would decrease the total energy N footprint (Shibata et al., 2014 ; Liang et al., 2016).
